# Instructions to compile and reproduce results
The code is organised in several files that include Python files and Fortran files. 
The first part of the project is done with Fortran to Python3 library, so to be able 
to compile and reproduce the code have an actualized version of f2py3 is needed.
In case that it is not found in the computer, it is usually installed together with Ptyhon3.

The second part of the project, the dynamic process, is done with pure Fortran because 
sintax of modern Fortran (2003) is used and is not supported in f2py3.
About how to compile, it can be done manually or with the Makefile.

## Manual compilation

To compile the code manually for the first part of the project do in the terminal:

>>> f2py3 -c -m network subroutine.f90

and

>>> f2py3 -c -m ass4 assignment4.py

From this compilation some .so files will be created. Later, open the scripts
asignment?.py (? can be 1, 4 or 5) in a Python interface and run it in the terminal.
That will generate the figures and files of each assignment.

The second part, the dynamic process, can be compiler manually doing in the terminal:

>>> gfortran module_dp.f90 dynamic_process.f90

This will generate a executable a.out and the program can be runned by doing in the terminal

>>> ./a.out

It is important to point out that for storing the output files of the simulation the folder 
output has to be created beforehand. Finally, to create the plots the script plots_dynamics.py
has to be used. It should be run in a python terminal as the rest of the .py programs.

## Makefile compilation
Since this is a little bothersome a Makefile has been created. This makefile automatically 
compiles the Fortran programs, those of f2py3 and the pure Fortran, and generates the directory
needed to store the output files. It is executed by doing in terminal:

>>> make

Later for running the program there is several possible executable: one for each assignment 
(1,4,5), one for the dinamic process and one to obtain the plots of the dynamic process. The 
order to execute are:

>>> run_ass1

>>> run_ass4

>>> run_ass5

>>> run_dynam

>>> run_plots_dyn

However it is recomended that the python programs are run using some python interface.
